TITLE: U.S. Eyes Sanctions Against Network It Believes Is Shipping Iranian Oil
SUMMARY: The U.S. believes a global network of companies has been helping Iran evade sanctions and export oil by blending it with Iraqi oil in ship-to-ship transfers at sea to hide its origins.

TITLE: How JetBlue Prevailed in Fight With Frontier for Spirit Airlines
SUMMARY: After a rough courtship, the carriers now face regulators and hurdles in merging the two different airlines.

TITLE: Consumers Have Powered Through the Pandemic---Until Now
SUMMARY: Recent government data show that household spending is increasingly strained and some companies are bracing for an economic downturn.

TITLE: Black and Hispanic Employees Often Get Stuck at the Lowest Rung of the Workplace
SUMMARY: A new comprehensive survey by McKinsey suggests that companies’ diversity efforts have largely missed the employees who stand to gain the most from them.

TITLE: Inside Ferrari's Plan to Enter the Electric-Vehicle Market
SUMMARY: The luxury sports-car company aims to start selling a fully electric vehicle in 2025. Can it do that and still be Ferrari?

TITLE: Silicon Valley Lurches Between Deep Cuts and Bold Spending
SUMMARY: The market correction is leaving some startups in crisis as others are taking employees on vacation.

TITLE: Falling Food Prices Ease Upward Pressure on Global Inflation
SUMMARY: Agricultural markets remain volatile as a result of war and hot weather. In the U.S., the impact on grocery bills might be muted.

TITLE: If This Is a Recession, We Might Not Know for Months
SUMMARY: The economy’s second-straight decline in output sparks debate—and the waiting game.

TITLE: Consumer Spending Grew Much Faster in June
SUMMARY: U.S. households’ spending rose 1.1% last month, the Commerce Department said, as annual inflation hit a new four-decade high, outpacing income growth.

TITLE: Inflation Hits Fresh Four-Decade High, According to Fed's Preferred Measure
SUMMARY: Consumer prices rose 6.8% in June from a year earlier, up from 6.3% in May and April, as measured by the Commerce Department’s personal-consumption expenditures price index. The gain in June marked the sharpest rise since January 1982.

TITLE: The U.S. Is Investing Big in Chips. So Is the Rest of the World.
SUMMARY: With the federal incentives now available, a key question will be to what extent the U.S. is able to land major chip-factory investments that would have gone elsewhere.

TITLE: Starbucks, Uber, CVS to Report Earnings Amid Shrinking Economy
SUMMARY: Companies across several industries will detail their respective performance during a quarter of economic contraction.

TITLE: The Microchip Era Is Giving Way to the Megachip Age
SUMMARY: To continue making our gadgets more powerful, engineers have worked out a new way to get around the barriers to making microchips faster: Just make them bigger.
